1
00:00:42,074 --> 00:00:47,287
It's hard to remember now,
but Europe was like this in 1944.

2
00:00:50,916 --> 00:00:55,838
The Second World War was in its
fifth year and still going Hitler's way.

3
00:00:56,380 --> 00:01:00,217
German troops
controlled most of Europe.

4
00:01:00,300 --> 00:01:03,512
D-day changed all that.

5
00:01:05,264 --> 00:01:10,310
D-day: June 6, 1944,
when the Allied forces,

6
00:01:10,394 --> 00:01:13,230
under their commander
General Eisenhower,

7
00:01:13,313 --> 00:01:16,608
landed on the northern coast of France.

8
00:01:16,692 --> 00:01:23,198
By July they were able to begin their own
offensive. By August Paris was liberated.

9
00:01:24,908 --> 00:01:28,203
Everywhere the Germans retreated.

10
00:01:29,162 --> 00:01:32,291
But with the Allied victories
came problems.

11
00:01:32,374 --> 00:01:36,837
Supplies still had to be driven from
Normandy, over 400 miles away,

12
00:01:36,920 --> 00:01:39,298
and became dangerously short.

13
00:01:39,381 --> 00:01:43,135
The Allied advance
began to come to a halt.

14
00:01:44,428 --> 00:01:47,931
Another problem
facing Eisenhower was this:

15
00:01:48,015 --> 00:01:51,852
his two most famous generals,
Patton who was in the south

16
00:01:51,935 --> 00:01:56,106
and Montgomery in the north,
disliked each other intensely.

17
00:01:56,190 --> 00:02:00,861
Their long-standing rivalry
had never been more fierce.

18
00:02:00,944 --> 00:02:04,364
There simply were
not enough supplies for both armies.

19
00:02:04,448 --> 00:02:07,618
Each wanted to be the one
to defeat the Germans.

20
00:02:07,701 --> 00:02:10,704
Each wanted to beat the other to Berlin.

21
00:02:11,663 --> 00:02:16,585
In September, 1944, Montgomery
devised a new and spectacular plan

22
00:02:16,668 --> 00:02:19,755
given the codename Market Garden.

23
00:02:19,838 --> 00:02:23,300
Eisenhower, under great pressure
from his superiors,

24
00:02:23,383 --> 00:02:25,636
finally sided with Montgomery,

25
00:02:25,719 --> 00:02:29,515
and Operation Market Garden
became a reality.

26
00:02:30,599 --> 00:02:35,604
The plan, like so many plans
in so many wars before it,

27
00:02:35,687 --> 00:02:39,274
was meant to end
the fighting by Christmas

28
00:02:39,358 --> 00:02:42,736
and bring the boys back home.

29
00:05:51,592 --> 00:05:57,848
ARNHEM, HOLLAND, SEPTEMBER 1944

30
00:06:25,167 --> 00:06:27,044
What is that noise?

31
00:06:31,507 --> 00:06:34,885
- Can I look out?
- No, they might shoot us.

32
00:06:41,016 --> 00:06:43,477
The Germans have collapsed.

33
00:06:47,856 --> 00:06:50,025
Then the war is over?

34
00:06:51,151 --> 00:06:52,361
Soon.

35
00:06:53,278 --> 00:06:54,988
But what is that noise?

36
00:06:58,450 --> 00:06:59,826
Panic.

37
00:07:43,245 --> 00:07:48,417
GERMAN WESTERN FRONT, ARMY H.Q.

38
00:08:10,272 --> 00:08:11,732
You may begin.

39
00:08:11,815 --> 00:08:16,028
May I first be permitted to say,
and I think I speak for all of us...

40
00:08:16,111 --> 00:08:19,072
how pleased we are,
Field Marshal Von Rundstedt...

41
00:08:19,198 --> 00:08:21,909
that you have been reappointed
commander of our forces in the west.

42
00:08:22,034 --> 00:08:24,119
Speeches are for victory celebrations.

43
00:08:24,244 --> 00:08:27,039
Let's get to the point. Air power?

44
00:08:27,623 --> 00:08:29,791
Air power, Field Marshal?

45
00:08:29,917 --> 00:08:31,084
Briefly, please.

46
00:08:32,544 --> 00:08:35,130
- Air power is minimal.
- Ammunition?

47
00:08:35,255 --> 00:08:36,840
Also minimal.

48
00:08:36,965 --> 00:08:39,092
Tanks... Troops... Replacements?

49
00:08:39,176 --> 00:08:40,761
- Minimal.
- Morale?

50
00:08:51,396 --> 00:08:53,065
Nonexistent.

51
00:08:55,359 --> 00:08:57,277
What do you think we should do?

52
00:08:59,071 --> 00:09:00,948
End the war, you fools.

53
00:09:02,699 --> 00:09:05,244
- Why in the world are you laughing?
- Excuse us.

54
00:09:05,327 --> 00:09:07,621
We have such confidence in you.

55
00:09:07,746 --> 00:09:10,123
Everyone knows you have
never lost a battle.

56
00:09:11,792 --> 00:09:15,462
I¡¯m still young. Give me time.

57
00:09:18,507 --> 00:09:21,426
The first thing we must do

58
00:09:21,510 --> 00:09:25,764
is to turn this rabble
into something like an army.

59
00:09:29,685 --> 00:09:33,146
Anything at all on when
they plan to invade Holland?

60
00:09:34,815 --> 00:09:36,984
They seem to have paused in Belgium.

61
00:09:37,067 --> 00:09:39,987
Most likely supply problems.

62
00:09:40,112 --> 00:09:41,989
Otherwise we can't imagine why.

63
00:09:44,992 --> 00:09:49,288
I think it's because we're retreating

64
00:09:49,371 --> 00:09:51,748
faster than they can advance.

65
00:10:23,280 --> 00:10:25,699
How many vehicles in the past hour?

66
00:10:25,782 --> 00:10:28,118
Fifty-four.

67
00:10:28,243 --> 00:10:31,038
And for the same hour yesterday?

68
00:10:31,121 --> 00:10:33,290
Ninety-eight.

69
00:10:33,415 --> 00:10:37,586
Last week your mother and l
could have captured Holland alone.

70
00:10:38,795 --> 00:10:40,923
Already the panic has stopped.

71
00:10:41,048 --> 00:10:44,801
It isn't over yet
and those idiots don't realise it.

72
00:10:44,927 --> 00:10:48,430
- War takes time.
- Listen to the expert.

73
00:10:48,555 --> 00:10:50,432
I was nine when they got here.

74
00:10:50,557 --> 00:10:53,477
Next month I¡¯ll be 14.
I ought to know something.

75
00:10:58,190 --> 00:11:00,400
Father, the Allies will come?

76
00:11:03,445 --> 00:11:05,239
But when?

77
00:11:05,989 --> 00:11:10,577
GENERAL BROWNlNG'S H.Q., ENGLAND

78
00:11:10,661 --> 00:11:13,330
I¡¯ve just got back to England
from Brussels,

79
00:11:13,413 --> 00:11:17,543
where I had a meeting this morning
with Field Marshal Montgomery.

80
00:11:17,626 --> 00:11:22,965
There was an earlier one with General
Eisenhower. They both feel, as I do,

81
00:11:23,048 --> 00:11:26,051
that when the field marshal¡¯s plan
has succeeded,

82
00:11:26,134 --> 00:11:30,514
we should be able to end the war
by Christmas in less than 100 days.

83
00:11:33,767 --> 00:11:37,437
Actually, the plan's really very simple.

84
00:11:37,521 --> 00:11:43,902
We're going to fly 35,000 men 300 miles
and drop them behind enemy lines.

85
00:11:44,278 --> 00:11:48,907
It'll be the largest
airborne operation ever mounted.

86
00:11:50,784 --> 00:11:56,039
Quite frankly, this kind of thing's
never been attempted before.

87
00:11:56,123 --> 00:11:59,084
- Where's this all gonna take place?
- Holland.

88
00:11:59,459 --> 00:12:02,045
- And when?
- I¡¯m coming to that now.

89
00:12:03,046 --> 00:12:04,381
Right.

90
00:12:07,134 --> 00:12:10,179
Ground forces: 30 Corps
commanded by General Horrocks.

91
00:12:10,262 --> 00:12:14,933
20,000 vehicles. And this, as you know,
is the German front line.

92
00:12:15,017 --> 00:12:17,686
We're going to lay a carpet,
as it were,

93
00:12:17,769 --> 00:12:21,648
of airborne troops,
over which 30th Corps can pass.

94
00:12:21,732 --> 00:12:24,985
We shall seize the bridges -
it's all a question of bridges -

95
00:12:25,068 --> 00:12:30,866
with thunderclap surprise,
and hold them until they can be secured.

96
00:12:30,949 --> 00:12:37,122
Now, first of all,
General Maxwell Taylor: Eindhoven.

97
00:12:37,206 --> 00:12:40,959
You take and hold
the bridges there with 101st.

98
00:12:42,711 --> 00:12:46,131
General Gavin, with your 82nd,

99
00:12:46,215 --> 00:12:50,177
you get Nijmegen.
You take and hold the bridges.

100
00:12:50,761 --> 00:12:53,388
And, Roy, you get the prize: Arnhem.

101
00:12:54,223 --> 00:12:56,600
Arnhem Bridge.

102
00:12:56,683 --> 00:12:59,645
- And you hold it.
- For how long?

103
00:13:00,562 --> 00:13:06,276
Well, Monty assures me that
30 Corps will do the 63 miles in

104
00:13:06,360 --> 00:13:08,153
two days.

105
00:13:08,237 --> 00:13:11,823
- 63 miles in two days.
- They'll handle that.

106
00:13:11,907 --> 00:13:14,952
I¡¯m sorry. General Sosabowski.

107
00:13:15,035 --> 00:13:19,581
You go with your Polish brigade
with Roy Urquhart. I¡¯m so sorry.

108
00:13:21,041 --> 00:13:23,293
Roy,

109
00:13:23,377 --> 00:13:27,840
when you've secured your bridge
and 30th Corps have got across it,

110
00:13:27,923 --> 00:13:33,220
we can turn east right into
the industrial heart of Germany - the Ruhr.

111
00:13:33,303 --> 00:13:39,184
Once we control their factories, there's
not much they can do. That is the plan.

112
00:13:40,060 --> 00:13:43,689
- And we go next Sunday.
- Seven days?

113
00:13:44,147 --> 00:13:49,027
Why not? The sooner we go, the better.
We've got them on the run.

114
00:13:51,655 --> 00:13:55,367
Is something troubling you,
General Sosabowski?

115
00:13:56,034 --> 00:14:01,123
- I¡¯ve said nothing.
- Precisely. Your silences are thunderous.

116
00:14:05,085 --> 00:14:09,339
General Browning, I am a Pole,

117
00:14:10,215 --> 00:14:13,302
considered by some to be smart.

118
00:14:13,385 --> 00:14:18,182
If that is so, it makes me
a member of a true minority group.

119
00:14:19,099 --> 00:14:22,519
Minority groups
are more comfortable in silence.

120
00:14:22,603 --> 00:14:26,732
Really? I should have thought the
opposite was true. But you do disapprove.

121
00:14:27,065 --> 00:14:30,694
I am thrilled that your great field marshal
has devised such a plan.

122
00:14:30,777 --> 00:14:33,864
I promise you
I will be properly ecstatic if it works.

123
00:14:33,947 --> 00:14:37,492
- When it works.
- Of course. When it works.

124
00:14:37,701 --> 00:14:40,120
Thank you.

125
00:14:40,954 --> 00:14:46,543
Well, now let's get down to the details.
First thing, we shall have to have a...

126
00:14:46,627 --> 00:14:49,713
From which direction will their
attack come, and who will command?

127
00:14:49,838 --> 00:14:51,715
Montgomery or Patton?

128
00:14:53,300 --> 00:14:55,511
- Model, what do you think?
- Patton.

129
00:14:56,553 --> 00:14:58,722
He is their best.

130
00:14:58,847 --> 00:15:01,266
Patton will lead the assault.

131
00:15:01,391 --> 00:15:04,478
I would prefer Montgomery

132
00:15:04,561 --> 00:15:06,980
but even Eisenhower isn't that stupid.

133
00:15:10,776 --> 00:15:13,237
Bittrich's panzer troops need some rest

134
00:15:13,362 --> 00:15:17,032
if they're to stop Patton.

135
00:15:17,115 --> 00:15:21,411
We should pull them back
somewhere safe.

136
00:15:21,537 --> 00:15:25,499
Safe, quiet, out of the way. But where?

137
00:15:25,582 --> 00:15:27,167
Arnhem?

138
00:15:31,713 --> 00:15:34,049
Arnhem.

139
00:15:34,466 --> 00:15:39,638
U.S. 82nd AlRBORNE DlVlSlON H.Q.,
ENGLAND

140
00:15:41,431 --> 00:15:45,310
- Why the emergency meeting?
- Keeping me abreast of the little changes.

141
00:15:45,394 --> 00:15:50,190
- How big are the little changes?
- With British understatement: gigantic.

142
00:15:50,274 --> 00:15:54,903
They can't get us all in. Too many men,
too much equipment, not enough planes.

143
00:15:54,987 --> 00:15:59,700
It's going to take three days to get the
men into Arnhem - Poles and the British.

144
00:15:59,783 --> 00:16:03,620
- How about us?
- Except for parachuting in daylight,

145
00:16:03,704 --> 00:16:07,624
- we have nothing to worry about.
- Daylight?

146
00:16:07,708 --> 00:16:11,378
- Has it ever been tried before?
- Not in a major drop.

147
00:16:11,461 --> 00:16:15,048
- You think there's a reason for that?
- Let's hope not.

148
00:16:15,132 --> 00:16:18,177
- What do you think?
- It's a no-moon period anyway.

149
00:16:18,260 --> 00:16:22,139
We have to go in daylight.
Just so they get us over the target area.

150
00:16:22,222 --> 00:16:27,644
- Half a mile away. I¡¯ll settle for that.
- I don't wanna hear anything else.

151
00:16:27,728 --> 00:16:31,398
- Is there anything else?
- Well, you're my Dutch advisor, Harry.

152
00:16:31,481 --> 00:16:33,567
I forgot to tell you something?

153
00:16:33,650 --> 00:16:38,071
Only that the Germans first tried to take
Nijmegen Bridge themselves in 1940,

154
00:16:38,155 --> 00:16:40,991
and got slaughtered.

155
00:16:45,162 --> 00:16:46,705
Go back!

156
00:16:49,500 --> 00:16:50,959
Go back!

157
00:16:52,836 --> 00:16:54,296
Do as I say!

158
00:16:54,379 --> 00:16:57,716
But my friend lives down the road.

159
00:16:59,009 --> 00:17:02,137
It's my birthday
and she has a present for me.

160
00:17:03,555 --> 00:17:05,766
Please let me through.

161
00:17:12,940 --> 00:17:14,983
All right. Be quick.

162
00:17:26,537 --> 00:17:28,163
Are you sure about the colours?

163
00:17:28,247 --> 00:17:30,624
I¡¯m sure, Father. Believe me.

164
00:17:33,752 --> 00:17:35,128
Model?

165
00:17:36,547 --> 00:17:39,383
A field marshal in Arnhem? Why?

166
00:17:40,509 --> 00:17:42,803
The British will have an explanation.

167
00:17:42,886 --> 00:17:44,805
Did you pass on
the message about the tanks?

168
00:17:44,888 --> 00:17:47,808
Of course. But Model is
something more important.

169
00:17:49,434 --> 00:17:52,521
You're a good boy and a wonderful spy.

170
00:17:52,604 --> 00:17:55,023
Now go and help
your mother with supper.

171
00:17:58,819 --> 00:18:00,612
Sir!

172
00:18:00,696 --> 00:18:04,116
- Yes, Fuller.
- We've got some information on tanks.

173
00:18:04,199 --> 00:18:06,493
Dutch underground reports from Arnhem.

174
00:18:06,577 --> 00:18:09,288
- Established their strength?
- No, but...

175
00:18:09,371 --> 00:18:11,957
- Have they been identified?
- Not by us, sir.

176
00:18:12,040 --> 00:18:16,003
- So it's the same rumours as before.
- I believe these rumours, sir.

177
00:18:16,086 --> 00:18:19,548
Why? The general consensus
is that our opposition

178
00:18:19,631 --> 00:18:22,426
will consist entirely
of Hitler youths or old men.

179
00:18:22,509 --> 00:18:27,014
I don't really know why, sir. Perhaps
because no one in intelligence does.

180
00:18:27,097 --> 00:18:33,103
I just want to be sure our airborne carpet
consists of live troops, not dead ones.

181
00:18:33,187 --> 00:18:36,690
I know everybody thinks
I¡¯m overanxious, sir.

182
00:18:36,773 --> 00:18:40,194
But I would like to order
another low-level reconnaissance.

183
00:18:40,277 --> 00:18:43,530
If that's all right with you, sir.

184
00:18:44,907 --> 00:18:47,242
Very well.

185
00:18:47,326 --> 00:18:48,952
All right, Wilson.

186
00:18:49,036 --> 00:18:50,496
Very well.

187
00:18:50,579 --> 00:18:53,207
- Fuller, Fuller.
- Yeah. Sir.

188
00:18:53,624 --> 00:18:57,461
I wouldn't be too concerned
about what people think of you.

189
00:18:57,544 --> 00:19:03,258
You happen to be somewhat brighter than
most of us. It tends to make us nervous.

190
00:19:14,520 --> 00:19:17,689
We'll do our utmost
to meet your tactical requirements.

191
00:19:18,023 --> 00:19:23,070
But, please, keep in mind the one factor
which is crippling all our plans.

192
00:19:23,153 --> 00:19:28,325
It may seem improbable to you, but we
are desperately short of transport aircraft.

193
00:19:28,408 --> 00:19:31,787
- I am aware of that.
- I¡¯m surprised that nobody told Monty

194
00:19:31,870 --> 00:19:34,206
when he dreamed up this operation.

195
00:19:34,289 --> 00:19:39,461
I need drop zones as close as possible
to the bridge. This area is no use at all.

196
00:19:39,545 --> 00:19:42,548
Can't have my chaps
landing on top of chimneys.

197
00:19:42,631 --> 00:19:46,009
Now, this looks inviting here.
What's the terrain like?

198
00:19:46,093 --> 00:19:51,056
Sorry, sir. Our reports indicate that
this terrain is too soft for glider landings.

199
00:19:51,139 --> 00:19:56,103
The nose digs in on touchdown, the thing
goes arse over tit... Total write-off.

200
00:19:56,186 --> 00:19:58,605
All right. What about there?

201
00:19:58,689 --> 00:20:02,985
No, afraid not, sir. After the drop
when we bank for our return,

202
00:20:03,068 --> 00:20:07,990
we run into a whole lot of flak and
rubbish from this Jerry airfield at Deelen.

203
00:20:08,073 --> 00:20:11,869
Presumably you're intending
to let us land somewhere.

204
00:20:12,536 --> 00:20:14,621
Ooh, yes. Hopefully, sir.

205
00:20:14,705 --> 00:20:20,752
But, as I was saying, we cannot afford to
lose a single aircraft. That is the problem.

206
00:20:21,336 --> 00:20:25,007
My problem is
I don't just need drop zones.

207
00:20:25,090 --> 00:20:28,302
I need drop zones I can hold and defend.

208
00:20:28,385 --> 00:20:31,388
The rest of my division
arrives with a second drop

209
00:20:31,471 --> 00:20:33,807
and General Sosabowski's with a third.

210
00:20:33,891 --> 00:20:37,519
I understand, sir. But we really think
we've found the right place.

211
00:20:37,603 --> 00:20:42,691
It's large enough for your needs,
it's flat and firm, and also easily defended.

212
00:20:43,233 --> 00:20:47,404
- Where the hell is it?
- It's not actually on this photograph.

213
00:20:47,487 --> 00:20:49,698
It should be... excuse me, sir.

214
00:20:49,781 --> 00:20:52,784
It would be about here, I think.

215
00:20:55,787 --> 00:20:59,875
- That could be ten miles from the bridge.
- Just under eight, actually.

216
00:20:59,958 --> 00:21:02,628
If you'd like to have a look at this.

217
00:21:03,837 --> 00:21:07,424
You see, the terrain is easy to traverse.

218
00:21:07,508 --> 00:21:11,136
All our information substantiates that.

219
00:21:12,221 --> 00:21:14,556
Yes, sir?

220
00:21:14,640 --> 00:21:17,518
Just making sure whose side you're on.

221
00:22:07,860 --> 00:22:11,238
Now, a drop zone
eight miles from Arnhem Bridge

222
00:22:11,321 --> 00:22:15,617
- might be thought to present problems.
- My God. He can't mean it.

223
00:22:15,701 --> 00:22:19,288
I¡¯m afraid he does.
He must know what he's doing.

224
00:22:19,371 --> 00:22:22,833
That's more than I know. Why should
he have the corner on the market?

225
00:22:22,916 --> 00:22:27,629
..cannot under any stretch
of the imagination be considered ideal.

226
00:22:27,713 --> 00:22:31,466
The gliders will bring in
a reconnaissance squadron of Jeeps

227
00:22:31,550 --> 00:22:34,344
fitted with twin Vickers machine guns.

228
00:22:34,428 --> 00:22:39,391
Now, the instant we land, they will
race ahead to the bridge and hold it

229
00:22:39,474 --> 00:22:44,688
- until the other battalions arrive on foot.
- They'll be able to secure both ends?

230
00:22:45,063 --> 00:22:48,317
- Most certainly.
- Good. You all know where I shall be.

231
00:22:48,400 --> 00:22:51,111
My headquarters will be
in the centre with 82nd.

232
00:22:51,195 --> 00:22:56,283
Remember we're all totally interlocked.
This is a bottom-to-top operation.

233
00:22:56,366 --> 00:22:59,203
101st pass 30 Corps on to 82nd.

234
00:22:59,286 --> 00:23:02,664
82nd pass them on to British Airborne.

235
00:23:02,748 --> 00:23:07,002
If any one group fails,
it's total failure for us all.

236
00:23:08,045 --> 00:23:11,840
All we need now
are three days of clear skies.

237
00:23:11,924 --> 00:23:14,676
Thank you, gentlemen, very much.

238
00:23:15,636 --> 00:23:17,930
Only the weather can stop us now.

239
00:23:18,305 --> 00:23:20,390
Weather! Chrystus!

240
00:23:24,186 --> 00:23:28,565
General Browning, what of the Germans?
Don't you think that since we know

241
00:23:28,649 --> 00:23:33,111
that Arnhem is so crucial to their safety,
they might know that too?

242
00:23:33,487 --> 00:23:38,116
The few troops in the area
are second class.

243
00:23:38,200 --> 00:23:42,788
They're not front-line calibre.
Not at all. Do you understand?

244
00:23:43,664 --> 00:23:46,875
Have more faith
in Montgomery's intelligence reports.

245
00:23:46,959 --> 00:23:49,503
He's done pretty well for us
in the last few years.

246
00:23:49,586 --> 00:23:52,714
I will tell you the extent of my faith.

247
00:23:53,674 --> 00:23:58,512
I¡¯m thinking of asking for a letter stating
that I was forced to act on your orders,

248
00:23:58,595 --> 00:24:01,348
in case my men are massacred.

249
00:24:02,432 --> 00:24:04,518
I see.

250
00:24:05,811 --> 00:24:07,896
Yes, I do see.

251
00:24:12,234 --> 00:24:14,319
Do you wish such a letter?

252
00:24:15,654 --> 00:24:17,239
No.

253
00:24:18,198 --> 00:24:22,286
- No, of course not.
- In the case of massacre,

254
00:24:22,369 --> 00:24:24,955
what difference would it make?

255
00:24:34,965 --> 00:24:37,593
- You mean you don't believe me, sir?
- Clearly not.

256
00:24:37,676 --> 00:24:41,054
All right, boys. NAAFI¡¯s up.
Take your break.

257
00:24:42,639 --> 00:24:46,393
- God Almighty!
- Sorry about that, sir. But what, then?

258
00:24:46,476 --> 00:24:51,690
The radios aren't strong enough to carry
from the drop zone to Arnhem Bridge.

259
00:24:51,773 --> 00:24:54,651
- You don't have any cigarettes, do you?
- No.

260
00:24:54,735 --> 00:24:58,155
They're perfectly OK. I¡¯ve used them
God knows how many times.

261
00:24:58,238 --> 00:25:00,908
You've told me that
God knows how many times.

262
00:25:00,991 --> 00:25:04,328
Well, I didn't have any problems
with them in the desert.

263
00:25:04,411 --> 00:25:08,040
Yes, I know. You see,
Colonel, what bothers me,

264
00:25:08,123 --> 00:25:10,459
what has me more than a bit disturbed,

265
00:25:10,542 --> 00:25:16,173
is that Holland being half underwater
is soggier than most deserts you find.

266
00:25:17,132 --> 00:25:19,343
Tends to have a lot more trees.

267
00:25:19,426 --> 00:25:23,180
- Any biscuits?
- Your biscuits are in your tin, sir.

268
00:25:23,931 --> 00:25:29,019
- Tell the general, if you're so certain.
- If I were, believe me, I would.

269
00:25:29,102 --> 00:25:32,439
- What if they really don't work?
- What difference will it make?

270
00:25:32,523 --> 00:25:35,067
The general will be
on the bridge by nightfall.

271
00:25:35,150 --> 00:25:40,072
He won't have to make contact
with the bridge if he's on it, will he, sir?

272
00:25:40,155 --> 00:25:44,076
Well... if anyone rocks the boat,

273
00:25:44,159 --> 00:25:46,870
it's not gonna be me.

274
00:25:50,707 --> 00:25:54,169
The regular projector chap's at lunch.
I¡¯ll have it in a moment.

275
00:25:54,253 --> 00:25:58,757
You're doing splendidly, Fuller.
Don't worry. I don't need lunch.

276
00:25:58,841 --> 00:26:00,759
Damn!

277
00:26:00,843 --> 00:26:05,055
Nearly there, sir.
It's really worth your time, sir. Believe me.

278
00:26:06,598 --> 00:26:08,058
There.

279
00:26:08,141 --> 00:26:11,144
Splendid view of the Dutch countryside.
No tanks.

280
00:26:11,228 --> 00:26:16,984
Wait a moment, sir. It's a lot clearer
in the next picture. If I can just...

281
00:26:17,985 --> 00:26:20,112
Now.

282
00:26:22,823 --> 00:26:26,702
- Next.
- Yes, sir. I¡¯ve had this one enlarged.

283
00:26:51,226 --> 00:26:55,606
Yes. I shouldn't worry about them.

284
00:26:57,816 --> 00:27:02,863
- But, sir, you see, they are tanks.
- I doubt if they're fully serviceable.

285
00:27:03,989 --> 00:27:05,991
- Still got guns.
- So have we.

286
00:27:07,284 --> 00:27:14,333
But, sir... if they weren't serviceable,
why would they try to conceal them?

287
00:27:14,416 --> 00:27:19,630
- Normal routine, Fuller.
- We keep getting reports from the Dutch.

288
00:27:19,713 --> 00:27:24,051
I¡¯ve read them!
And so has Field Marshal Montgomery.

289
00:27:24,134 --> 00:27:27,763
Now, look here. There have been
thousands of photographs

290
00:27:27,846 --> 00:27:32,559
from this sortie and all the others.
How many of them have shown tanks?

291
00:27:32,643 --> 00:27:35,771
- Just these, sir.
- You seriously want us to cancel

292
00:27:35,854 --> 00:27:41,944
the biggest operation mounted since
D-day because of three photographs?

293
00:27:47,282 --> 00:27:49,618
- No, sir.
- 16 consecutive drops

294
00:27:49,701 --> 00:27:53,705
have been cancelled in the last
few months for one reason or another.

295
00:27:53,789 --> 00:27:58,669
But this time the party's on.
And no one is going to call it off.

296
00:28:00,379 --> 00:28:03,465
Is that fully understood?

297
00:28:03,549 --> 00:28:06,051
Yes, sir.

298
00:28:06,677 --> 00:28:09,054
GENERAL HORROCKS' XXX CORPS. H.Q.

299
00:28:09,137 --> 00:28:12,349
LEOPOLDSBURG ON THE
BELGlAN-DUTCH BORDER

300
00:28:28,115 --> 00:28:29,741
Thank you, Waddy.

301
00:28:32,411 --> 00:28:34,454
Thank you, gentlemen!

302
00:28:35,622 --> 00:28:39,668
Do sit down, gentlemen. Please sit down.

303
00:28:41,086 --> 00:28:43,672
Look after these for me, will you?

304
00:28:48,677 --> 00:28:50,846
Thank you, gentlemen. Thank you.

305
00:28:53,473 --> 00:28:57,769
Gentlemen, this is a story
that you will tell your grandchildren.

306
00:28:57,853 --> 00:29:01,231
And mightily bored they'll be!

307
00:29:01,481 --> 00:29:04,610
The plan is called
Operation Market Garden.

308
00:29:04,693 --> 00:29:09,781
Market is the airborne element
and Garden the ground forces - that's us.

309
00:29:09,865 --> 00:29:13,911
Now, this is our position
on the Belgian border here.

310
00:29:14,203 --> 00:29:18,665
Tomorrow three airborne divisions
will begin landing in Holland.

311
00:29:18,749 --> 00:29:25,005
35,000 men taking off from 24 airfields in
troop-carrying planes or towed in gliders.

312
00:29:25,547 --> 00:29:30,719
The American 101st here,
around Eindhoven.

313
00:29:30,802 --> 00:29:35,474
The American 82nd here,
south of Nijmegen,

314
00:29:35,557 --> 00:29:41,522
and our own 1st Airborne boys
and a Polish brigade here at Arnhem,

315
00:29:41,605 --> 00:29:45,400
64 miles behind enemy lines.

316
00:29:47,945 --> 00:29:54,827
Now, their job is to take and hold
all the bridges in these three areas.

317
00:29:54,910 --> 00:30:00,457
Our job is to punch a hole
through the German front line here

318
00:30:00,541 --> 00:30:04,002
and then drive like hell up this road,

319
00:30:04,086 --> 00:30:08,841
linking up with each airborne division
on the way up.

320
00:30:09,174 --> 00:30:12,678
Speed is the vital factor.

321
00:30:14,137 --> 00:30:17,641
The plan is to reach Eindhoven
in two to three hours,

322
00:30:17,724 --> 00:30:20,602
and Arnhem in two to three days.

323
00:30:21,311 --> 00:30:24,147
That, gentlemen, is the prize.

324
00:30:24,231 --> 00:30:29,653
The bridge over the Rhine.
The last bridge between us and Germany.

325
00:30:30,070 --> 00:30:33,782
Kickoff will be at 1435 hours
tomorrow afternoon.

326
00:30:33,866 --> 00:30:37,369
The lrish Guards and Colonel Vandeleur
will take the lead.

327
00:30:37,452 --> 00:30:40,330
- Christ. Not us again.
- What d'you say to that, Joe?

328
00:30:40,956 --> 00:30:43,625
Delighted, sir. Truly delighted.

329
00:30:44,376 --> 00:30:49,882
I¡¯ve selected you to lead us, not only due
to your extraordinary fighting ability,

330
00:30:49,965 --> 00:30:54,303
but also because, in the unlikely event
that the Germans ever get you,

331
00:30:54,386 --> 00:30:58,015
they will assume from your attire
that you're a wretched peasant

332
00:30:58,098 --> 00:31:02,769
and immediately send you on your way.

333
00:31:04,104 --> 00:31:09,067
Now, maintaining the speed of our
advance will no doubt be tough going,

334
00:31:09,151 --> 00:31:11,320
as it's a single highway.

335
00:31:11,403 --> 00:31:17,784
But, no matter what, we must reach
those 1st Airborne boys in 48 hours.

336
00:31:17,868 --> 00:31:21,455
Now, gentlemen,
I¡¯m not saying that this will be

337
00:31:21,538 --> 00:31:24,666
the easiest party
that we've ever attended.

338
00:31:24,750 --> 00:31:28,295
But I still wouldn't miss it for the world.

339
00:31:28,378 --> 00:31:34,259
I like to think of this as one of those
American Western films.

340
00:31:34,343 --> 00:31:39,890
The paratroops lacking substantial
equipment, always short of food.

341
00:31:39,973 --> 00:31:42,768
These are the besieged homesteaders.

342
00:31:42,851 --> 00:31:46,146
The Germans,
well, naturally, they're the bad guys.

343
00:31:46,230 --> 00:31:49,900
And 30 Corps, we, my friends,

344
00:31:49,983 --> 00:31:54,238
are the cavalry on the way to the rescue!

345
00:31:57,741 --> 00:32:00,035
COLONEL FROST'S QUARTERS

346
00:32:00,118 --> 00:32:03,247
BRlTlSH 1st AlRBORNE DlVlSlON,
ENGLAND

347
00:32:10,879 --> 00:32:13,882
Oh. Do you want me
to pack that as well, sir?

348
00:32:13,966 --> 00:32:16,760
- No, thank you, Wicks. I¡¯ll carry it.
- Sir.

349
00:32:18,095 --> 00:32:23,058
- You haven't forgotten my golf clubs?
- They'll be coming later in the staff car.

350
00:32:23,141 --> 00:32:24,977
What about...?

351
00:32:25,060 --> 00:32:26,979
Sorry, sir?

352
00:32:27,062 --> 00:32:29,565
What about my dinner jacket?

353
00:32:30,649 --> 00:32:33,402
Are you sure you'll be needing that, sir?

354
00:32:33,485 --> 00:32:35,988
Well, let's hope so.

355
00:32:38,115 --> 00:32:41,118
U.S. 101st AlRBORNE DlVlSlON, ENGLAND

356
00:32:41,201 --> 00:32:43,328
This is chock full of vitamins.

357
00:32:43,412 --> 00:32:46,331
Here, Eddie. Have a little strength.

358
00:32:51,295 --> 00:32:53,755
Hey, where'd you put that?

359
00:32:53,839 --> 00:32:57,176
- Dammit, Eddie. Give it back.
- Right.

360
00:32:57,885 --> 00:32:59,970
There you are.

361
00:33:00,762 --> 00:33:03,473
I wish you hadn't done that.

362
00:33:05,601 --> 00:33:09,605
You see, my problem is I¡¯m not totally
crazy about the prospect of dying.

363
00:33:09,688 --> 00:33:11,773
So don't die.

364
00:33:13,275 --> 00:33:16,820
- That garbage isn't gonna keep you alive.
- Well, what is?

365
00:33:16,904 --> 00:33:18,989
What is? Well...

366
00:33:19,990 --> 00:33:23,619
- Not gettin' shot.
- What can guarantee that?

367
00:33:23,702 --> 00:33:26,205
Nothin' - for sure.

368
00:33:29,833 --> 00:33:32,085
You will.

369
00:33:32,169 --> 00:33:35,255
- I will what?
- You tell me, Eddie.

370
00:33:35,339 --> 00:33:37,841
You tell me I won't die.

371
00:33:38,550 --> 00:33:42,721
- All right. You won't die.
- No, no. Guarantee me.

372
00:33:42,804 --> 00:33:45,933
I want you to guarantee me I won't die.

373
00:33:51,772 --> 00:33:54,316
I guarantee you.

374
00:34:06,870 --> 00:34:08,997
Come on.

375
00:34:09,081 --> 00:34:12,125
Let's get some food in ya. Come on.

376
00:34:12,209 --> 00:34:14,294
I wasn't kidding.

377
00:34:18,882 --> 00:34:22,386
Hey, Eddie! Were you kidding?

378
00:34:23,762 --> 00:34:25,848
Major Fuller.

379
00:34:27,015 --> 00:34:30,269
My name is Sims. Mind a bit of company?

380
00:34:31,854 --> 00:34:33,939
Of course not, sir.

381
00:34:35,524 --> 00:34:38,026
Busy times.

382
00:34:38,110 --> 00:34:40,612
You must be exhausted.

383
00:34:43,240 --> 00:34:45,742
Are you? Exhausted?

384
00:34:46,827 --> 00:34:48,912
Who isn't?

385
00:34:49,830 --> 00:34:53,709
We've been getting reports
from a number of your friends.

386
00:34:53,792 --> 00:34:58,672
They're worried about you.
They think perhaps you need a rest.

387
00:34:59,882 --> 00:35:03,635
We all need rest.
Why are you saying this to me?

388
00:35:05,721 --> 00:35:08,515
Is it because I rocked the boat?

389
00:35:09,808 --> 00:35:13,937
I¡¯m a doctor.
I¡¯m only concerned with your health.

390
00:35:15,522 --> 00:35:19,234
I think perhaps you ought to take
a bit of sick leave.

391
00:35:20,486 --> 00:35:22,571
But why?

392
00:35:24,781 --> 00:35:27,493
I¡¯m not ill or anything.

393
00:35:29,077 --> 00:35:31,747
I haven't done anything wrong.

394
00:35:31,830 --> 00:35:35,417
No, of course not. You're just a little tired.

395
00:35:37,461 --> 00:35:39,838
Yes.

396
00:35:39,922 --> 00:35:42,424
I am tired.

397
00:35:46,261 --> 00:35:48,764
I think perhaps we might go.

398
00:35:51,225 --> 00:35:54,353
Can't it be stopped?

399
00:35:54,436 --> 00:35:56,021
No.

400
00:35:57,272 --> 00:36:01,193
I don't want to be left behind. Please.

401
00:36:02,110 --> 00:36:04,822
It's out of my hands, laddie.

402
00:36:17,751 --> 00:36:20,462
I didn't want to miss the party.

403
00:37:55,891 --> 00:37:58,393
Come on. Move it, buddy.

404
00:38:09,530 --> 00:38:13,575
- Come on! Move yourselves!
- Get up there. Move on down.

405
00:38:18,789 --> 00:38:21,208
Home, sweet home.

406
00:38:23,961 --> 00:38:28,257
When you think we only had seven days
to get everything organised, it's quite a...

407
00:38:28,340 --> 00:38:32,511
Bloody miracle. It took six months
to set up the D-day drop.

408
00:38:32,594 --> 00:38:35,556
And that was only half as big as this.

409
00:38:36,682 --> 00:38:38,600
- How d'you feel?
- Fine.

410
00:38:38,684 --> 00:38:42,062
I¡¯ll feel even better when we're in Holland.

411
00:38:42,145 --> 00:38:45,107
A few months back
when I was appointed to this command

412
00:38:45,190 --> 00:38:48,902
I told you I had never jumped
but thought I ought to give it a go.

413
00:38:48,986 --> 00:38:52,114
- Well, you did me a big favour.
- Oh, really? What?

414
00:38:52,197 --> 00:38:57,035
You said ''Roy, you're far too old
for that kind of thing and much too large.''

415
00:38:57,119 --> 00:38:59,413
Did l? What was the favour?

416
00:38:59,496 --> 00:39:03,876
Well, I didn't quite
tell you everything at the time.

417
00:39:05,169 --> 00:39:10,257
- But I¡¯m prone to airsickness.
- Good gracious! Every flight?

418
00:39:11,592 --> 00:39:14,595
We'll soon find out, won't we?

419
00:42:53,146 --> 00:42:55,232
Soon be home, Harry.

420
00:43:02,656 --> 00:43:06,326
- Better than the desert, eh, sir?
- What was that?

421
00:43:06,410 --> 00:43:09,121
Easier than walking, sir.

422
00:43:11,081 --> 00:43:13,792
If you say so, Hancock.

423
00:43:27,556 --> 00:43:30,058
Yeah. Fine, sir.

424
00:43:32,436 --> 00:43:36,481
The artillery should be able to clear
the way pretty well - your initial advance.

425
00:43:36,565 --> 00:43:39,276
We'll move as soon as
their barrage has got going.

426
00:43:39,359 --> 00:43:44,281
- Yes, that's absolutely fine.
- Follow behind it as close as we can.

427
00:43:44,364 --> 00:43:48,619
But this isn't going to be the pushover
that everybody seems to think it is.

428
00:43:48,702 --> 00:43:51,413
No, I didn't think so.

429
00:43:51,497 --> 00:43:55,918
Morning, Alan! Your sleeping beauties
know there's a war on, do they?

430
00:43:56,001 --> 00:43:59,213
Is it true that the Germans
have put more troops ahead of us?

431
00:43:59,296 --> 00:44:02,925
Yes. They don't intend
to just let us walk in the front door.

432
00:44:03,008 --> 00:44:07,387
Hello, Bob! Hope that's not
my funeral they're going to!

433
00:44:07,846 --> 00:44:11,767
And I¡¯m still worried about
having to throw everything up this road.

434
00:44:11,850 --> 00:44:14,978
But there's no alternative. Morning, Tom!

435
00:44:15,062 --> 00:44:17,981
So I¡¯ve decided
to run the road like a railway.

436
00:44:18,065 --> 00:44:23,320
Nobody will be allowed to put any vehicle
on that road without my permission.

437
00:44:23,403 --> 00:44:25,489
- Including me?
- Good luck, sir!

438
00:44:25,572 --> 00:44:29,117
You too! Especially you, Joe.

439
00:44:29,201 --> 00:44:34,540
Morning, Derek! Glad to see
somebody knows where we're going.

440
00:44:39,169 --> 00:44:42,464
Time, Joe. That's the killer.

441
00:44:42,548 --> 00:44:46,009
We can't afford to drop behind schedule.

442
00:44:46,593 --> 00:44:50,305
So, for God's sake,
keep your tanks on the move.

443
00:44:59,731 --> 00:45:02,359
Good God Almighty.

444
00:45:02,442 --> 00:45:07,114
That's just the 101st. The other
two groups are on the northern route.

445
00:45:08,323 --> 00:45:10,576
H-hour in 90 minutes.

446
00:45:10,659 --> 00:45:14,079
- I¡¯d better be going, sir.
- Right you are, Joe.

447
00:45:14,163 --> 00:45:16,290
Any last-minute changes, Bob?

448
00:45:16,373 --> 00:45:20,085
If we run into difficulty, we call in
the air force with purple smoke.

449
00:45:20,169 --> 00:45:24,756
- First class! And good luck, Joe!
- Thank you, sir.

450
00:45:24,840 --> 00:45:31,054
- Do you think you'll be able to manage it?
- I¡¯ve got nothing else planned for today.

451
00:46:35,035 --> 00:46:37,120
Ta.

452
00:46:38,080 --> 00:46:41,959
I told you
you should have had the bloody thing out.

453
00:46:58,100 --> 00:47:00,227
What the hell¡¯s that?

454
00:47:00,310 --> 00:47:02,396
It's flak.

455
00:47:04,481 --> 00:47:06,525
GENERAL BlTTRlCH'S H.Q.

456
00:47:06,608 --> 00:47:08,652
SOUTH OF ARNHEM

457
00:47:08,735 --> 00:47:10,279
General Bittrich!

458
00:47:10,404 --> 00:47:12,406
In here, Matthias.

459
00:47:26,587 --> 00:47:29,298
Fantastic, isn't it?

460
00:47:29,423 --> 00:47:33,260
Just once to have
such power in my hands.

461
00:47:40,184 --> 00:47:43,061
- Red on!
- Red on.

462
00:50:25,265 --> 00:50:29,353
If there's no more opposition than this
on the road, we shall be all right.

463
00:50:45,410 --> 00:50:47,496
B Company to me!

464
00:50:47,579 --> 00:50:50,249
A Company over there!

465
00:50:59,341 --> 00:51:04,012
FlELD MARSHAL MODEL'S H.Q.
HARTENSTElN HOTEL NEAR ARNHEM

466
00:51:08,141 --> 00:51:11,603
Excuse the interruption,
Field Marshal, but...

467
00:51:11,728 --> 00:51:14,189
British paratroopers have landed...

468
00:51:15,107 --> 00:51:18,026
three kilometres from here.

469
00:51:18,110 --> 00:51:20,654
Why should they do that?

470
00:51:21,738 --> 00:51:24,158
There is nothing important here.

471
00:51:27,119 --> 00:51:30,372
Me! I am important.

472
00:51:31,165 --> 00:51:33,542
They must all be coming
just to capture me.

