02:02:58,757 --> 02:03:01,134
There's God knows how many
out there already.

946
02:03:01,385 --> 02:03:05,263
- You mean it's over, sir?
- I didn't say that, did l?

947
02:03:05,347 --> 02:03:10,519
We've paid for that bridge and we're
going to collect, but I need tank support.

948
02:03:10,602 --> 02:03:15,315
Well, you've got it, Jimmy. The Grenadier
Guards will be happy to oblige.

949
02:03:15,399 --> 02:03:17,609
- Is that all right, Alex?
- Absolutely.

950
02:03:17,692 --> 02:03:20,153
It's not just tanks. I need boats.

951
02:03:20,237 --> 02:03:23,281
If 30 Corps were American,
we would have boats.

952
02:03:23,365 --> 02:03:26,284
- Mike?
- I think we might have a few somewhere.

953
02:03:26,368 --> 02:03:29,746
- Can you get them here by tonight?
- It won't be easy, sir.

954
02:03:29,830 --> 02:03:34,501
We've got one road, 10-mile traffic jams
on it and Germans throwing shells at us.

955
02:03:34,584 --> 02:03:39,548
- I don't know quite what we can do...
- Except try. You can do that, can't you?

956
02:03:39,631 --> 02:03:41,717
Thank you, gentlemen. Thank you.

957
02:03:41,800 --> 02:03:44,636
Now, look here. About these boats...

958
02:03:44,720 --> 02:03:46,805
What is your opinion?

959
02:03:48,014 --> 02:03:51,685
The general¡¯s a bit scratchy today,
but it's nothing personal.

960
02:03:51,768 --> 02:03:56,189
When we dropped on Sunday,
I think he cracked his spine.

961
02:04:05,699 --> 02:04:10,120
- How many boats have we got, then?
- About six in each truck.

962
02:04:23,717 --> 02:04:26,386
Where's Major Cook, soldier?

963
02:04:26,470 --> 02:04:28,889
- I think over there, sir.
- Thank you.

964
02:04:44,196 --> 02:04:46,698
Julian, where the hell are you?

965
02:04:47,491 --> 02:04:49,993
Here, sir.

966
02:04:54,122 --> 02:04:56,750
We're going to take
Nijmegen Bridge tonight.

967
02:04:56,833 --> 02:05:00,962
- What's the best way to take a bridge?
- Both ends at once.

968
02:05:01,046 --> 02:05:04,132
I¡¯m sending two companies
across the river by boat.

969
02:05:04,216 --> 02:05:08,637
I need a man with
very special qualities to lead.

970
02:05:08,720 --> 02:05:09,888
Go on, sir.

971
02:05:09,971 --> 02:05:14,351
He's gotta be tough enough to do it and
he's gotta be experienced enough to do it.

972
02:05:14,434 --> 02:05:18,188
Plus one more thing.
He's gotta be dumb enough to do it.

973
02:05:19,981 --> 02:05:22,484
Start getting ready.

974
02:05:28,907 --> 02:05:31,118
What was all that about, Major?

975
02:05:31,201 --> 02:05:34,663
Well, someone's
come up with a real nightmare.

976
02:05:36,957 --> 02:05:38,208
A real nightmare.

977
02:05:39,793 --> 02:05:41,878
Come on! Keep moving!

978
02:05:50,053 --> 02:05:52,806
We got word from
the Dutch resistance at Arnhem.

979
02:05:52,889 --> 02:05:57,310
It's not going well for the British. Their
main force never reached the bridge.

980
02:05:57,394 --> 02:05:59,563
Those that did are hanging on.

981
02:05:59,646 --> 02:06:01,982
- And Urquhart?
- His back is to the river.

982
02:06:02,065 --> 02:06:05,902
The Germans have trapped his men
in a pocket, and they're squeezing it.

983
02:06:05,986 --> 02:06:08,739
How long can he hold?

984
02:06:10,031 --> 02:06:12,367
Where are those goddamn boats?

985
02:06:28,800 --> 02:06:31,344
Just keep it clear! Right!

986
02:06:32,596 --> 02:06:38,602
They're no further than we thought.
Julian, we have a little change in plans.

987
02:06:38,685 --> 02:06:41,980
We're to make the crossing in daylight.

988
02:06:42,064 --> 02:06:44,441
- Daylight?
- Traffic's all screwed up.

989
02:06:44,524 --> 02:06:48,403
By the time we're ready, it'll be 0800.
That's when we go.

990
02:06:48,487 --> 02:06:50,072
Fine.

991
02:06:50,155 --> 02:06:55,077
I¡¯d like to wait and go tomorrow night,
but the British can't hold.

992
02:06:55,160 --> 02:06:57,496
Better by daylight.

993
02:06:58,038 --> 02:06:59,956
Much.

994
02:07:05,712 --> 02:07:09,591
- Any news of the boats?
- No. We're switching... You want some?

995
02:07:09,674 --> 02:07:11,051
No, thank you.

996
02:07:11,134 --> 02:07:13,929
We're switching the start till nine,
to make sure.

997
02:07:14,012 --> 02:07:16,640
You start laying smoke just before we go.

998
02:07:16,723 --> 02:07:18,725
Fine, fine.

999
02:07:18,809 --> 02:07:24,523
They're gonna get creamed. Your smoke
screen's gonna be their only protection.

1000
02:07:24,606 --> 02:07:27,526
Don't worry. We'll cover you.

1001
02:07:28,402 --> 02:07:29,569
Please.

1002
02:07:39,830 --> 02:07:43,959
OK. Can I have your attention, please?
Can I have your attention?

1003
02:07:44,042 --> 02:07:48,046
Our nine o'clock departure
has been postponed till ten.

1004
02:07:48,130 --> 02:07:51,675
So you can all have an extra hour's
fun and relaxation.

1005
02:07:51,758 --> 02:07:55,011
Major, we got any more information
on those boats?

1006
02:07:55,804 --> 02:07:58,515
We're reliably informed that they float.

1007
02:07:58,598 --> 02:08:04,020
Outside of that, we don't know squat. Not
how many, not how heavy, not how big.

1008
02:08:04,104 --> 02:08:08,024
We are sure that the river's wide
and that the current is strong.

1009
02:08:08,108 --> 02:08:11,778
As more cheery information comes
my way, I¡¯ll be happy to pass it along.

1010
02:08:11,862 --> 02:08:16,491
In the meantime, just think of this
as on-the-job training.

1011
02:08:18,201 --> 02:08:21,121
What's the matter? No sense of humour?

1012
02:08:22,330 --> 02:08:24,416
Goddamn it!

1013
02:08:25,709 --> 02:08:27,502
We go at noon.

1014
02:08:30,380 --> 02:08:34,134
- These lorries have priority, sir.
- Yes, I know, but...

1015
02:08:40,015 --> 02:08:43,060
Come on! Clear it off the road!

1016
02:09:14,257 --> 02:09:19,054
You men are probably wondering
why I¡¯ve called us here together.

1017
02:09:20,263 --> 02:09:24,351
I¡¯ve reached a decision
that I¡¯d like to share with you all.

1018
02:09:25,644 --> 02:09:30,399
I intend to go across like George
Washington. Standing on the prow.

1019
02:09:30,482 --> 02:09:33,485
You guys can do the rowing.

1020
02:09:40,242 --> 02:09:43,036
That's it! Move 'em out!

1021
02:09:59,594 --> 02:10:02,431
- What the...?
- What did you expect? Destroyers?

1022
02:10:02,514 --> 02:10:05,225
Come on! Put it together!

1023
02:10:34,504 --> 02:10:36,131
What else can you see besides smoke?

1024
02:10:36,214 --> 02:10:39,634
Nothing yet, but they are
going to try a river assault.

1025
02:10:40,761 --> 02:10:42,137
It will fail.

1026
02:10:42,262 --> 02:10:44,890
Of course it will fail, but...

1027
02:10:44,973 --> 02:10:47,934
what do we do if it doesn't?

1028
02:10:48,018 --> 02:10:50,562
I ask your permission
to blow up the bridge.

1029
02:10:50,687 --> 02:10:52,147
Out of the question.

1030
02:10:54,441 --> 02:10:57,319
I understand, Field Marshal.

1031
02:10:57,444 --> 02:11:01,698
They will not cross the river
and we will blow no bridges.

1032
02:11:01,823 --> 02:11:03,492
Have all demolition charges
been checked?

1033
02:11:03,617 --> 02:11:06,369
Yes, sir. Everything is wired and ready.

1034
02:11:06,495 --> 02:11:09,247
Captain Krafft is standing by as ordered.

1035
02:11:11,041 --> 02:11:14,002
The bridge will not
fall into enemy hands.

1036
02:11:15,128 --> 02:11:17,631
As soon as the first
British tank starts to cross...

1037
02:11:19,132 --> 02:11:20,675
I¡¯ll blow it sky-high.

1038
02:11:33,688 --> 02:11:36,942
- Let's get going!
- All right! Go! Go! Go!

1039
02:11:55,627 --> 02:11:59,715
When you get to the water, go on!
Don't wait! Go!

1040
02:12:20,152 --> 02:12:25,282
If you don't have an oar,
use your rifle butt! Anything! Row!

1041
02:12:47,929 --> 02:12:50,557
One... two.

1042
02:12:59,608 --> 02:13:03,403
The current's taking us down!
Stay to your right!

1043
02:13:09,659 --> 02:13:12,412
- Support fire ordered, sir.
- Thank you.

1044
02:13:15,207 --> 02:13:17,918
Row!

1045
02:13:34,601 --> 02:13:36,686
Get down!

1046
02:13:40,315 --> 02:13:43,693
Go! Go! Go! Go!

1047
02:13:48,407 --> 02:13:50,742
Hail Mary, full of grace.

1048
02:13:51,201 --> 02:13:54,663
Hail Mary, full of grace. Hail Mary...

1049
02:13:57,207 --> 02:14:00,419
Hail Mary, full of grace. Hail Mary...

1050
02:14:31,992 --> 02:14:35,287
We're drifting! Pull to your left!
Come on! Pull!

1051
02:14:39,040 --> 02:14:41,585
Come on! Keep rowing!

1052
02:14:50,343 --> 02:14:52,429
Stay down!

1053
02:14:54,014 --> 02:14:56,475
Come on, boys!

1054
02:15:05,442 --> 02:15:07,527
Thy will be done.

1055
02:15:08,528 --> 02:15:11,907
Thy will be done.

1056
02:15:19,372 --> 02:15:22,125
Come on! Let's go!

1057
02:15:39,768 --> 02:15:41,561
Snipers!

1058
02:15:52,447 --> 02:15:55,325
Help me! Help me.

1059
02:16:15,554 --> 02:16:18,014
Go up the side!

1060
02:16:28,734 --> 02:16:32,112
- Can we make it through the tunnel?
- No way, sir.

1061
02:16:33,947 --> 02:16:36,825
- Up the bank!
- With you, sir.

1062
02:16:49,629 --> 02:16:51,715
Cover.

1063
02:17:00,432 --> 02:17:02,934
Come on.

1064
02:17:33,632 --> 02:17:36,259
Come on! Schnell! Schnell!

1065
02:17:45,977 --> 02:17:51,525
Sergeant, take four across - draw fire.
Harry and I¡¯ll go up the side. You cover.

1066
02:17:51,608 --> 02:17:52,943
Go!

1067
02:17:59,866 --> 02:18:02,202
- Go on.
- Come on! Let's go!

1068
02:18:22,806 --> 02:18:24,141
Are you ready?

1069
02:18:24,224 --> 02:18:25,350
Yes, General.

1070
02:18:42,492 --> 02:18:44,286
Dammit!

1071
02:19:33,835 --> 02:19:37,047
My God, they're only
18 kilometres from Arnhem.

1072
02:19:38,173 --> 02:19:40,634
Who can stop them now?

1073
02:19:42,135 --> 02:19:44,262
No one.

1074
02:20:15,752 --> 02:20:17,462
Oh, hell.

1075
02:20:17,546 --> 02:20:19,631
Any chance, Whitney?

1076
02:20:19,715 --> 02:20:23,802
- Not unless we're relieved soon, sir.
- Harry?

1077
02:20:23,885 --> 02:20:27,848
- Try and get him down to the cellar.
- Very good, sir.

1078
02:20:52,414 --> 02:20:56,001
It's working.
I¡¯m through to HQ. Where's the colonel?

1079
02:20:56,084 --> 02:20:57,627
- Down below.
- Get him!

1080
02:20:57,711 --> 02:21:00,172
- Colonel Frost!
- What is it?

1081
02:21:00,255 --> 02:21:02,340
Up top!

1082
02:21:02,424 --> 02:21:05,010
Up top, sir!

1083
02:21:05,093 --> 02:21:08,638
- It's headquarters, sir. On the radio.
- Coming!

1084
02:21:12,267 --> 02:21:15,771
Sunray on set. Pass your message. Over.

1085
02:21:15,854 --> 02:21:21,026
- What's your situation, Johnny? Over.
- I hadn't expected the pleasure, sir.

1086
02:21:21,109 --> 02:21:23,195
We're holding out.

1087
02:21:25,155 --> 02:21:28,784
We need reinforcements
and, above all, ammunition. Over.

1088
02:21:28,867 --> 02:21:34,122
I¡¯m not sure if it's a case of us
coming for you... or you coming for us.

1089
02:21:34,206 --> 02:21:38,919
- Well, we'll just wait for 30 Corps, then.
- That would probably be best.

1090
02:21:39,503 --> 02:21:42,547
Very reassuring talking to you, sir.

1091
02:21:43,840 --> 02:21:48,762
I¡¯m sorry, Johnny. Getting stuck on that
bloody bridge, four days on your own.

1092
02:21:48,845 --> 02:21:53,433
- Have you anything else for me?
- No, sir. I¡¯ll call when our friends arrive.

1093
02:21:53,517 --> 02:21:56,019
- Over.
- All right.

1094
02:21:56,770 --> 02:21:59,731
Good luck. Out.

1095
02:22:06,363 --> 02:22:08,740
- Sergeant Tomblin!
- Here, sir!

1096
02:22:08,824 --> 02:22:10,992
I¡¯m coming over!

1097
02:22:13,662 --> 02:22:16,164
Sergeant Taylor!

1098
02:22:25,757 --> 02:22:30,262
I don't understand. Why aren't you
moving? What's the matter with you?

1099
02:22:30,345 --> 02:22:32,889
Those are British troops at Arnhem.

1100
02:22:32,973 --> 02:22:35,100
They're hurt - bad.

1101
02:22:35,350 --> 02:22:38,228
You're not gonna stop. Not now.

1102
02:22:38,311 --> 02:22:40,731
I¡¯m sorry. We have our orders.

1103
02:22:40,814 --> 02:22:46,111
We busted our asses getting here. Half
my men are killed and you just stop...

1104
02:22:46,194 --> 02:22:48,989
and drink tea?

1105
02:22:49,072 --> 02:22:51,408
We're now facing a different situation.

1106
02:22:51,491 --> 02:22:55,454
We can't lead with tanks.
Jerry will pick us off like sitting ducks.

1107
02:22:55,537 --> 02:23:01,084
Our infantry are still fighting in Nijmegen.
When they get here, we'll move on.

1108
02:23:04,713 --> 02:23:07,215
Must you do everything by the book?

1109
02:23:07,299 --> 02:23:10,886
Our orders are to wait for the infantry.

1110
02:23:10,969 --> 02:23:13,055
I¡¯m sorry, but there it is.

1111
02:23:20,645 --> 02:23:22,105
Sir.

1112
02:23:24,524 --> 02:23:26,610
It's Major Carlyle, sir.

1113
02:23:40,707 --> 02:23:42,793
All right. I¡¯m all right.

1114
02:23:50,634 --> 02:23:53,887
- Hello, Harry.
- Hello, Johnny.

1115
02:23:55,847 --> 02:23:58,558
Things not so good, huh?

1116
02:24:04,523 --> 02:24:07,401
I¡¯ve been meaning to ask you something

1117
02:24:07,484 --> 02:24:12,823
and I haven't because I know you were
so anxious that I should,

1118
02:24:12,906 --> 02:24:16,410
and I wouldn't give you the satisfaction.

1119
02:24:18,036 --> 02:24:23,250
But why the hell do you always
carry that bloody umbrella?

1120
02:24:24,376 --> 02:24:26,878
- Memory.
- What?

1121
02:24:27,963 --> 02:24:30,465
Bad memory.

1122
02:24:32,509 --> 02:24:36,304
Always forgot the password.

1123
02:24:39,057 --> 02:24:43,228
I knew no Jerry would ever carry one.

1124
02:24:45,564 --> 02:24:52,821
I had to prove I was an Englishman.

1125
02:25:06,960 --> 02:25:09,046
Harry?

1126
02:25:19,681 --> 02:25:22,809
Get back! Back into the houses!

1127
02:25:34,488 --> 02:25:38,200
Hello, 30 Corps. Please hurry up.

1128
02:25:38,283 --> 02:25:40,535
Please.

1129
02:25:45,916 --> 02:25:48,418
- Nothing, sir.
- Thank you, Corporal.

1130
02:25:48,502 --> 02:25:51,213
It's no use in any event.
Take my boot off, Wicks.

1131
02:26:01,598 --> 02:26:04,309
We're out of ammunition anyway.

1132
02:26:05,727 --> 02:26:08,730
Right, off you go, Wicks.
Join the rest of the lads.

1133
02:26:08,814 --> 02:26:11,441
- Get back to the main force.
- What about you, sir?

1134
02:26:11,525 --> 02:26:16,238
I¡¯ll be all right.
We just didn't make it this time, did we?

1135
02:27:37,402 --> 02:27:39,571
My general says, ''Please take it.''

1136
02:27:39,905 --> 02:27:44,618
''It's very good chocolate.
Your planes dropped it to us yesterday.''

1137
02:27:57,631 --> 02:27:59,716
English.

1138
02:28:04,596 --> 02:28:06,556
Red on!

1139
02:28:07,933 --> 02:28:10,018
Red on.

1140
02:28:12,270 --> 02:28:14,356
Action stations!

1141
02:28:14,439 --> 02:28:17,859
God bless Field Marshal Montgomery.

1142
02:30:00,170 --> 02:30:06,009
Would five minutes be too much?

1143
02:30:07,803 --> 02:30:09,679
Just five minutes respite.

1144
02:30:12,891 --> 02:30:16,019
Dear God

1145
02:30:16,103 --> 02:30:18,522
grant these young men

1146
02:30:19,731 --> 02:30:23,110
die in peace and quiet.

1147
02:30:46,466 --> 02:30:49,636
I¡¯m sorry, lads,
but you're going to have to move.

1148
02:30:58,562 --> 02:31:00,981
Please.

1149
02:31:01,064 --> 02:31:03,150
Take my hand.

1150
02:31:07,112 --> 02:31:10,574
We're a bit late with this one, mate.

1151
02:31:16,288 --> 02:31:19,875
''Surely he shall deliver thee
from the snare of the fowler

1152
02:31:19,958 --> 02:31:23,920
and from the noisome pestilence.''

1153
02:31:24,004 --> 02:31:29,843
''He shall cover thee with his feathers,
and under his wings shalt thou trust:

1154
02:31:29,926 --> 02:31:33,597
his truth shall be
thy shield and buckler.''

1155
02:31:52,282 --> 02:31:54,785
There you go. Head back.

1156
02:31:55,660 --> 02:31:58,163
You'll be all right now, chum.

1157
02:32:04,753 --> 02:32:07,422
Can it get worse?

1158
02:32:07,506 --> 02:32:10,634
Oh, yes, much worse.

1159
02:32:12,969 --> 02:32:17,599
ELST - 5 MlLES FROM ARNHEM

1160
02:32:26,900 --> 02:32:29,569
Bring up the bulldozer.

1161
02:32:40,747 --> 02:32:42,833
Stretcher-bearer!

1162
02:32:46,002 --> 02:32:48,088
Help me!

1163
02:32:48,797 --> 02:32:50,882
Stretcher!

1164
02:32:56,888 --> 02:32:59,933
Morphia! Taffy, I must have morphia!

1165
02:33:00,016 --> 02:33:03,311
Morphia's only for the people
who are really hurt.

1166
02:33:03,395 --> 02:33:05,897
I thought I was really hurt.

1167
02:33:05,981 --> 02:33:08,066
Well, you're wrong.

1168
02:33:09,025 --> 02:33:12,279
No, I asked him to come over,
but Dr Spaander does agree.

1169
02:33:12,362 --> 02:33:15,532
- We've got to do something.
- Yes. What? Good day, Doctor.

1170
02:33:15,615 --> 02:33:20,704
General Urquhart, we have no more space
and we have no more supplies.

1171
02:33:20,787 --> 02:33:25,417
And since a prisoner of war has
more chance than no chance at all,

1172
02:33:26,043 --> 02:33:30,714
I have a mind to ask the Germans to
accept our wounded into their hospitals

1173
02:33:31,256 --> 02:33:36,178
if we could arrange evacuation.
Have I your permission to try?

1174
02:33:36,261 --> 02:33:38,513
Certainly. If Weaver agrees.

1175
02:33:38,597 --> 02:33:43,101
But I hardly think the Germans will.
Those are our guns out there.

1176
02:33:43,185 --> 02:33:48,440
That's 30 Corps. I don't think my
permission's going to be your problem.

1177
02:33:59,534 --> 02:34:02,162
I¡¯ve come with a message
from General Urquhart.

1178
02:34:02,245 --> 02:34:06,333
- How you manage that?
- I swam the Rhine, sir.

1179
02:34:06,416 --> 02:34:09,544
I¡¯m afraid the radios are all up the spout.

1180
02:34:09,628 --> 02:34:13,465
The general asks if you'll
get your men across the river.

1181
02:34:13,548 --> 02:34:16,635
We've been holding out for six days now.

1182
02:34:16,718 --> 02:34:20,430
Any help at all would be
of considerable assistance.

1183
02:34:20,514 --> 02:34:23,892
- You'll swim back with reply?
- Yes, sir.

1184
02:34:24,935 --> 02:34:27,646
Well, we can't swim.

1185
02:34:27,729 --> 02:34:30,190
Not with equipment.

1186
02:34:30,273 --> 02:34:32,984
We have small rubber boats, that's all.

1187
02:34:33,068 --> 02:34:35,695
Rubber dinghies may be
a bit flimsy for the Rhine.

1188
02:34:35,779 --> 02:34:37,781
I agree.

1189
02:34:43,120 --> 02:34:45,664
Tell the general we're coming.

1190
02:34:45,747 --> 02:34:47,833
We're coming tonight.

1191
02:34:48,542 --> 02:34:49,835
Yes, sir.

1192
02:37:44,176 --> 02:37:48,472
- Not possible.
- If you would just say yes,

1193
